font-style: inherit;">y =</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"Country"</span>) <span class="sc" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">+</span></span>
<span id="cb5-8">  <span class="fu" style="color: #4758AB;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">theme_minimal</span>()</span></code></pre></div></div>
<div class="cell-output-display">
<div>
<figure class="figure">
<p><img src="https://your-website-url.example.com/posts/Untitled/index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png" class="img-fluid figure-img" width="672"></p>
</figure>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The plot shows the amount of money each country has sold in chocolate. Australia has sold the most, just as was shown in the amount of boxes shipped plot. The main difference here is that Canada has dropped from second in the previous plot to fourth in this plot meaning that they have sold more boxes for lower prices.</p>
</section>
<section id="conclusions" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="conclusions">Conclusions</h3>
<p>The plots each show something about how much It is interesting to note that, despite Canada being at the top in average price per box of chocolate, they are also much higher (second) in total boxes sold than in total cost sold (fourth). This is interesting to note because this would imply that Canada has lower costs per box of chocolate (as they are selling more boxes yet less money), but earlier plot show that Canada has the highest average price per box of chocolates. This further demonstrates that it is important to look at many different visualizations as the same data can tell different stories depending on how it is displayed.</p>
</section>
<section id="connection-to-class-ideas" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="connection-to-class-ideas">Connection to Class Ideas</h3>
<p>The first set of plots clearly shows when bar plots are a bad idea. They demonstrate the importance of using the right visualization when looking at only plots and not any data or statistical tests. All of the graphs demonstrate concepts learned in class of appropriate colour schemes, colouring by variables, and fixing aesthetics to create a better visualization. I utilized concepts from the grammar of graphics unit to enhance the visualizations and make them both easier and more appealing to look at.</p>


</section>
</section>

 ]]></description>
